text: A thirty-second note (also called a demisemiquaver) is a note with a value of of the duration of a whole note which is how it gets the name. It has 3 flags or beams. A single thirty-second note is always stemmed with flags, while two or more are usually beamed in groups.Gerou, Tom (1996). Essential Dictionary of Music Notation, p.211. Alfred. In the \frac 4 4 time signature it has a value of of a beat. ==References== Category:Note values
title: Thirty-second note
